1
00:00:23,273 --> 00:00:25,901
<i>Friends, let me introduce myself.</i>

2
00:00:26,276 --> 00:00:28,487
<i>Peltzer's the name.
Rand Peltzer.</i>

3
00:00:29,071 --> 00:00:30,906
<i>That's me there on the corner.</i>

4
00:00:31,532 --> 00:00:32,908
<i>I'm an inventor.</i>

5
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:35,285
<i>And I have a story to tell.</i>

6
00:00:35,619 --> 00:00:38,080
<i>I know. Who hasn't got a story?</i>

7
00:00:38,330 --> 00:00:41,166
<i>Well, nobody's got
a story like this one.</i>

8
00:00:41,375 --> 00:00:43,043
<i>Nobody.</i>

9
00:00:43,335 --> 00:00:45,796
<i>It all started here in Chinatown.</i>

10
00:00:46,213 --> 00:00:48,799
<i>I was trying to move
a little merchandise...</i>

11
00:00:49,049 --> 00:00:51,385
<i>...maybe find a present for my kid.</i>

12
00:00:51,677 --> 00:00:53,804
<i>I tried this one place.</i>

13
00:00:58,433 --> 00:01:00,102
Wait a minute.

14
00:01:01,061 --> 00:01:02,229
What's down here?

15
00:01:02,437 --> 00:01:03,647
This is it.

16
00:01:03,939 --> 00:01:06,316
This is your grandfather's store?

17
00:01:07,317 --> 00:01:08,569
Come on.

18
00:01:10,153 --> 00:01:13,073
No wonder you gotta drag
people in off the street.

19
00:01:18,745 --> 00:01:20,956
Go ahead, mister. Look around.

20
00:01:21,164 --> 00:01:23,333
See if there's something you like.

21
00:01:43,103 --> 00:01:44,229
Are these things real?

22
00:01:44,438 --> 00:01:47,065
I told you, everything's real.

23
00:01:49,526 --> 00:01:51,862
You do have interesting
artifacts here...

24
00:01:52,112 --> 00:01:53,947
...but there's one thing
you don't have.

25
00:01:54,197 --> 00:01:55,365
And what's that?

26
00:01:55,741 --> 00:01:58,994
Let me show you.
I'm an inventor. I made this.

27
00:01:59,620 --> 00:02:02,789
The Bathroom Buddy.
The invention of the century.

28
00:02:03,040 --> 00:02:07,377
It eliminates the need to carry
heavy luggage when you travel.

29
00:02:07,669 --> 00:02:10,547
You got yourself your shaving mirror...

30
00:02:10,756 --> 00:02:14,885
...your toothbrush, a toothpick.
You got toenail clippers...

31
00:02:15,886 --> 00:02:16,970
...a nail file...

32
00:02:17,304 --> 00:02:19,806
...and you got yourself a dental mirror.

33
00:02:20,015 --> 00:02:22,184
This is gonna revolutionize traveling.

34
00:02:22,684 --> 00:02:25,270
Let's just say,
for the sake of argument...

35
00:02:25,520 --> 00:02:27,898
...that you're on a bus,
a plane or a train.

36
00:02:28,565 --> 00:02:31,234
You forgot to brush your teeth.

37
00:02:31,902 --> 00:02:35,405
You got yourself a bad
case of dragon breath.

38
00:02:36,990 --> 00:02:38,450
Bad breath.

39
00:02:38,659 --> 00:02:40,035
What do you do?

40
00:02:40,202 --> 00:02:42,829
No problem, friend. All you do is...

41
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:44,748
...you take your toothbrush out...

42
00:02:45,123 --> 00:02:46,708
...and you push this button.

43
00:02:48,210 --> 00:02:50,045
That's absolutely no problem.

44
00:02:50,754 --> 00:02:52,798
Cleans up easily.

45
00:02:53,048 --> 00:02:55,926
What I'd like to do, sir,
is give you my card.

46
00:02:56,176 --> 00:02:59,429
Rand Peltzer. "Fantastic Ideas
for a Fantastic World."

47
00:02:59,638 --> 00:03:01,139
I make the illogical logical.

48
00:03:02,015 --> 00:03:03,725
I can get you these.

49
00:03:04,017 --> 00:03:06,311
I can get them by the dozen
if you'd like.

50
00:03:10,315 --> 00:03:11,733
What do you think?

51
00:03:13,652 --> 00:03:14,945
What do you think?

52
00:03:18,281 --> 00:03:19,950
Where's that coming from?

53
00:03:39,136 --> 00:03:40,137
What is that?

54
00:03:40,303 --> 00:03:41,513
<i>Mogwai.</i>

55
00:03:44,850 --> 00:03:45,976
What's he doing?

56
00:03:46,226 --> 00:03:47,394
Singing.

57
00:03:48,103 --> 00:03:50,313
He does that sometimes.

58
00:03:56,278 --> 00:03:58,822
I gotta have him.
He's incredible.

59
00:03:59,823 --> 00:04:01,116
Tell you what I'll do.

60
00:04:01,366 --> 00:04:04,244
- I'll give you $100 for him.
- No.

61
00:04:04,661 --> 00:04:07,789
I've gotta have him. It's a present
for my son for Christmas.

62
00:04:07,998 --> 00:04:09,750
It's what I've been looking for.

63
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:12,502
I've been everywhere.
I'll give you $200.

64
00:04:12,794 --> 00:04:14,212
That's $200!

65
00:04:14,588 --> 00:04:15,839
I'm sorry.

66
00:04:16,214 --> 00:04:19,092
<i>Mogwai</i> not for sale.

67
00:04:20,427 --> 00:04:22,679
You said everything here was for sale.

68
00:04:22,888 --> 00:04:23,889
Grandfather!

69
00:04:24,097 --> 00:04:27,851
With <i>mogwai</i> comes much responsibility.

70
00:04:28,059 --> 00:04:31,396
I cannot sell him at any price.

71
00:04:37,235 --> 00:04:40,030
Wait outside. I'll be right out.

72
00:04:40,238 --> 00:04:41,615
Just go.

73
00:04:51,541 --> 00:04:54,127
Okay, mister, here it is.

74
00:04:55,253 --> 00:04:56,546
What about your grandfather?

75
00:04:56,713 --> 00:04:59,549
Forget what he said. He's crazy.
We need the money.

76
00:04:59,716 --> 00:05:01,218
Do you want it or not?

77
00:05:01,426 --> 00:05:02,677
I want it.

78
00:05:04,429 --> 00:05:07,098
<i>There's three rules
you've gotta follow.</i>

79
00:05:07,349 --> 00:05:08,725
<i>What kind of rules?</i>

80
00:05:09,059 --> 00:05:10,393
<i>Keep him out of the light.</i>

81
00:05:10,602 --> 00:05:13,563
<i>He hates bright light,
especially sunlight.</i>

82
00:05:13,730 --> 00:05:14,940
<i>It'll kill him.</i>

83
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:18,735
<i>And keep him away from water.
Don't get him wet.</i>

84
00:05:18,944 --> 00:05:22,739
<i>But the most important rule,
the rule you can never forget...</i>

85
00:05:22,948 --> 00:05:26,201
<i>...no matter how much he cries
or how much he begs...</i>

86
00:05:26,451 --> 00:05:30,288
<i>...never, never feed him
after midnight. Got it?</i>

87
00:05:30,497 --> 00:05:31,873
<i>Sure. Whatever you say.</i>

88
00:05:32,082 --> 00:05:34,876
<i>Thanks. And have a merry Christmas.</i>

89
00:05:42,717 --> 00:05:45,470
<i>You're rolling with Rockin' Ricky Rialto...</i>

90
00:05:45,720 --> 00:05:48,515
<i>...the voice of Kingston Falls, U.S.A.!</i>

91
00:06:22,007 --> 00:06:23,383
Alex...

92
00:06:23,800 --> 00:06:25,510
Getting close to Christmas.

93
00:06:25,760 --> 00:06:28,054
You'll get stuck with a lot of trees again.

94
00:06:28,305 --> 00:06:31,349
- I thought I'd see you about now.
- Ow!

95
00:06:31,558 --> 00:06:32,934
What the hell is this?

96
00:06:33,894 --> 00:06:35,645
What are you doing in there?

97
00:06:35,896 --> 00:06:37,397
Don't ask.

98
00:06:37,647 --> 00:06:39,900
Alex, I came to get my tree.

99
00:06:40,150 --> 00:06:42,944
Pete, take that tree
to Mr. Anderson's truck.

100
00:06:44,821 --> 00:06:46,156
What do you say, Alex?

101
00:06:46,406 --> 00:06:48,491
You can spare one
for the sheriff's station.

102
00:06:48,700 --> 00:06:51,244
I paid for mine, Frank.

103
00:07:39,376 --> 00:07:41,002
Billy, you need a jump?

104
00:07:41,419 --> 00:07:44,506
No, thanks, Mr. Futterman.
I'm late for work as it is.

105
00:07:44,756 --> 00:07:47,592
These goddamn foreign cars
always freeze up on you.

106
00:07:47,926 --> 00:07:51,012
You don't find American
machinery doing that.

107
00:07:51,304 --> 00:07:52,430
See that plow?

108
00:07:52,806 --> 00:07:55,225
Hasn't given me a day's
trouble in 15 years.

109
00:07:55,433 --> 00:07:57,143
You know why?
Kentucky Harvester.

110
00:07:57,435 --> 00:08:01,523
It ain't some foreign piece of crap.
That's a Kentucky Harvester.

111
00:08:02,023 --> 00:08:05,026
If I wanna keep my job,
I should be going now.

112
00:08:05,235 --> 00:08:06,987
How's your comic strip coming?

113
00:08:07,445 --> 00:08:11,282
I expect to see you in the funnies
with "Smilin' Jack," "Li'l Abner."

114
00:08:11,491 --> 00:08:13,785
They don't run those comics anymore.

115
00:08:13,994 --> 00:08:15,245
They don't?

116
00:08:15,662 --> 00:08:17,247
Come on, Barn.

117
00:08:17,747 --> 00:08:19,958
Say hello to your wife, okay?

118
00:08:20,166 --> 00:08:21,626
So long, Billy.

119
00:08:25,755 --> 00:08:28,091
Goddamn foreign cars.

120
00:08:52,615 --> 00:08:53,616
Hey, doctor.

121
00:08:53,783 --> 00:08:55,201
Morning, Billy.

122
00:09:16,222 --> 00:09:18,850
- Morning, Tom.
- Hey, Billy. Barney.

123
00:09:29,819 --> 00:09:32,322
Get in there and be quiet.

124
00:09:50,548 --> 00:09:53,176
- You just made it.
- Again.

125
00:09:53,760 --> 00:09:55,345
Will you sign this petition?

126
00:09:55,553 --> 00:09:57,430
Sure. What's it for?

127
00:09:57,639 --> 00:09:59,682
To declare Dorry's pub a landmark.

128
00:09:59,933 --> 00:10:02,352
Mrs. Deagle's trying
to take his lease away.

129
00:10:02,644 --> 00:10:03,686
His too?

130
00:10:03,853 --> 00:10:07,107
Yeah, she says it's a dive,
a public nuisance.

131
00:10:07,357 --> 00:10:09,359
That's where my dad proposed to my mom.

132
00:10:09,526 --> 00:10:13,196
That's where everybody's dad proposed
to their mom. Cross your "T."

133
00:10:17,492 --> 00:10:18,535
Thanks.

134
00:10:26,126 --> 00:10:27,627
Good morning, Mrs. Deagle.

135
00:10:27,877 --> 00:10:29,462
What's good about it?

136
00:10:32,882 --> 00:10:34,092
Klutz!

137
00:10:36,886 --> 00:10:38,513
Watch it, watch it!

138
00:10:39,013 --> 00:10:41,891
40, 60, 80...

139
00:10:48,815 --> 00:10:51,276
Two hundred. Thank you.

140
00:10:51,734 --> 00:10:53,027
- Mrs. Deagle?
- What?

141
00:10:53,236 --> 00:10:56,197
I just wanted you to know
that Joe got another job.

142
00:10:56,447 --> 00:10:57,740
My husband, Joe Harris.

143
00:10:57,949 --> 00:10:59,701
And I've taken up some sewing.

144
00:10:59,951 --> 00:11:01,703
What are you trying to tell me?

145
00:11:02,245 --> 00:11:04,914
Neither of us will be
paid for two weeks.

146
00:11:05,123 --> 00:11:07,083
Couldn't you get Mr. Corben...

147
00:11:07,584 --> 00:11:09,460
...to give us a little more time?

148
00:11:09,669 --> 00:11:10,837
Mrs. Harris...

149
00:11:11,004 --> 00:11:13,298
...the bank and I have
the same purpose in life...

150
00:11:13,548 --> 00:11:15,425
...to make money.

151
00:11:15,633 --> 00:11:17,302
Not to support a lot of...

152
00:11:17,510 --> 00:11:18,678
...deadbeats.

153
00:11:20,138 --> 00:11:22,640
Mrs. Deagle, it's Christmas!

154
00:11:26,436 --> 00:11:29,731
Now you know what to ask
Santa for, don't you?

155
00:11:31,983 --> 00:11:33,610
Mommy, I'm hungry.

156
00:11:33,985 --> 00:11:36,237
Yes, honey. So am I.

157
00:11:41,993 --> 00:11:44,871
This is what's left of my
imported Bavarian snowman.

158
00:11:45,121 --> 00:11:47,874
Your dog broke it this morning!

159
00:11:49,500 --> 00:11:50,793
I'm terribly sorry.

160
00:11:51,002 --> 00:11:52,545
Tell me how much I owe you...

161
00:11:52,754 --> 00:11:54,339
I don't want money.

162
00:11:57,217 --> 00:11:59,469
I want your dog.

163
00:12:02,472 --> 00:12:03,723
Barney?

164
00:12:04,474 --> 00:12:06,517
Give him to me.

165
00:12:06,726 --> 00:12:09,854
I'll take him to the kennel.
They'll put him to sleep.

166
00:12:10,063 --> 00:12:13,358
It'll be quick and painless,
compared to what I could do to him.

167
00:12:14,150 --> 00:12:15,526
What could you do?

168
00:12:18,613 --> 00:12:21,282
I'll catch the beast myself.

169
00:12:22,325 --> 00:12:24,410
Then he'll get what he deserves.

170
00:12:24,619 --> 00:12:27,163
A slow, painful death.

171
00:12:28,289 --> 00:12:31,918
Maybe I'll put him in my
spin dryer on high heat.

172
00:12:33,127 --> 00:12:34,295
That'd do it.

173
00:12:37,715 --> 00:12:38,883
Barney!

174
00:12:39,425 --> 00:12:40,551
Barney!

175
00:12:42,178 --> 00:12:44,138
Barney, will you get off of her?

176
00:12:44,347 --> 00:12:46,933
My dear lady, are you all right?

177
00:12:47,141 --> 00:12:50,395
I have a very weak heart.
I can't stand a shock like that!

178
00:12:50,603 --> 00:12:52,563
What is that dog doing in here?

179
00:12:52,814 --> 00:12:54,524
This is a bank, not a pet store.

180
00:12:54,691 --> 00:12:55,692
Very good, Gerald.

181
00:12:55,900 --> 00:12:57,193
He wouldn't hurt you.

182
00:12:57,402 --> 00:13:00,321
Excuses, excuses.
You're just like your father.

183
00:13:00,613 --> 00:13:04,826
I've listened to his excuses
for 10 years, the loser!

184
00:13:05,034 --> 00:13:07,954
As for you, you mangy cur...

185
00:13:08,329 --> 00:13:10,039
...I'll get you...

186
00:13:10,873 --> 00:13:12,750
...when you least expect it!

187
00:13:13,209 --> 00:13:14,627
Oh, my heart!

188
00:13:14,877 --> 00:13:17,755
I must apologize for this most unusual...

189
00:13:17,964 --> 00:13:19,632
You putz.

190
00:13:23,845 --> 00:13:25,722
The old bat never looked better.

191
00:13:26,139 --> 00:13:27,849
It's great. You're doing fine.

192
00:13:28,474 --> 00:13:29,684
Thanks.

193
00:13:30,059 --> 00:13:31,561
Hello, Gerald.

194
00:13:31,811 --> 00:13:34,856
If it isn't Captain Clip-on.

195
00:13:35,106 --> 00:13:38,484
Guess who almost applied
for unemployment today?

196
00:13:38,693 --> 00:13:40,987
- I give up.
- You.

197
00:13:41,195 --> 00:13:44,073
But Mr. Corben had second thoughts.

198
00:13:44,490 --> 00:13:46,909
He gets so sentimental
about the holidays.

199
00:13:47,118 --> 00:13:48,828
Imagine that.

200
00:13:49,579 --> 00:13:51,581
I would've fired you in a second.

201
00:13:52,206 --> 00:13:54,083
Merry Christmas to you too.

202
00:13:54,250 --> 00:13:56,127
Excuse me, Mr. Jones.

203
00:13:57,795 --> 00:13:59,464
Hey, Peltzer.

204
00:13:59,672 --> 00:14:02,800
Look, I'm a junior vice president at 23.

205
00:14:03,009 --> 00:14:06,387
By the time I'm 25, I'm gonna
have Mr. Corben's job.

206
00:14:06,846 --> 00:14:08,973
By the time I'm 30,
I'll be a millionaire.

207
00:14:09,182 --> 00:14:10,808
Look at you.

208
00:14:11,184 --> 00:14:13,936
You're practically supporting
your whole family.

209
00:14:14,520 --> 00:14:16,189
The world's changing.

210
00:14:16,397 --> 00:14:18,858
You gotta change with it.
You gotta be tough.

211
00:14:19,275 --> 00:14:22,278
Tough? And no one's
tougher than you, Ger?

212
00:14:23,738 --> 00:14:25,948
Don't call me that.
My name's Gerald.

213
00:14:26,157 --> 00:14:27,450
Can I get you a drink?

214
00:14:27,658 --> 00:14:30,119
Give me a vodka martini.
Shake, don't stir.

215
00:14:30,286 --> 00:14:31,329
You work here?

216
00:14:31,537 --> 00:14:34,123
Weeknights so Dorry doesn't
have to pay an extra waitress.

217
00:14:34,290 --> 00:14:35,291
That's great.

218
00:14:35,458 --> 00:14:38,753
Yeah, that's swell, if you
like working for nothing.

219
00:14:38,961 --> 00:14:42,215
Two more rounds for the
pool table, on the house.

220
00:14:43,633 --> 00:14:45,218
You haven't seen my new apartment.

221
00:14:45,426 --> 00:14:47,261
I haven't seen your old apartment.

222
00:14:48,054 --> 00:14:51,808
We're talking cable.
Can we have dinner tomorrow night?

223
00:14:53,351 --> 00:14:54,727
I'm working.

224
00:14:55,728 --> 00:14:59,148
Why don't you tell Dorry you're sick?
He can't dock your pay.

225
00:15:08,324 --> 00:15:09,826
Billy, is that you?

226
00:15:10,034 --> 00:15:11,577
Yeah, Mom, it's me.

227
00:15:11,786 --> 00:15:13,746
I'm in the kitchen.

228
00:15:15,832 --> 00:15:17,500
<i>Merry Christmas!</i>

229
00:15:21,087 --> 00:15:23,673
<i>Merry Christmas, movie house!</i>

230
00:15:24,090 --> 00:15:26,342
<i>Merry Christmas, emporium!</i>

231
00:15:26,843 --> 00:15:29,178
- Hi, Mom.
- Hi, sweetie.

232
00:15:29,512 --> 00:15:31,013
Do you need any help?

233
00:15:31,514 --> 00:15:33,391
Yeah, you could do the eggs.

234
00:15:33,891 --> 00:15:35,184
Thanks.

235
00:16:00,918 --> 00:16:04,964
Dad's machines work so well
the first couple of weeks, then...

236
00:16:05,214 --> 00:16:06,716
Use the sink.

237
00:16:12,305 --> 00:16:13,973
Is something wrong?

238
00:16:14,891 --> 00:16:17,101
No, it's a sad movie.

239
00:16:20,730 --> 00:16:22,064
How was your day?

240
00:16:22,273 --> 00:16:23,566
It was fine.

241
00:16:26,319 --> 00:16:28,529
Come on, what is it?
What's wrong?

242
00:16:29,363 --> 00:16:32,533
Mrs. Deagle called again this afternoon.

243
00:16:36,954 --> 00:16:40,082
Let's not talk about it now.
Don't say anything to Dad.

244
00:16:40,291 --> 00:16:41,542
Fine with me.

245
00:16:48,674 --> 00:16:50,343
Hi, sweetheart!

246
00:16:52,803 --> 00:16:55,181
- Welcome home.
- Hey, Dad.

247
00:16:56,599 --> 00:16:59,018
I'm glad you're back.
How was the trip?

248
00:16:59,185 --> 00:17:00,186
It was great.

249
00:17:00,353 --> 00:17:03,064
The Miracle Company,
who has the Kitchen Companion...

250
00:17:03,272 --> 00:17:06,150
...might be interested
in the Bathroom Buddy.

251
00:17:06,359 --> 00:17:07,777
Great!

252
00:17:10,780 --> 00:17:12,323
- Thanks!
- You'll like this.

253
00:17:13,199 --> 00:17:14,867
What is it? A birdcage?

254
00:17:15,451 --> 00:17:18,913
No, don't shake it. Open it now.
It won't wait till Christmas.

255
00:17:22,166 --> 00:17:23,459
It's a puppy, isn't it?

256
00:17:24,126 --> 00:17:25,294
Yeah, I can tell.

257
00:17:25,503 --> 00:17:26,963
It's a new car.

258
00:17:33,094 --> 00:17:35,805
- Honey, would you dim the lights?
- Sure.

259
00:17:36,013 --> 00:17:38,391
Dim the lights?
Does it glow in the dark?

260
00:17:38,599 --> 00:17:41,102
It's important. Trust me.

261
00:17:42,436 --> 00:17:44,063
Go ahead, open it.

262
00:18:06,377 --> 00:18:07,670
What is it?

263
00:18:07,878 --> 00:18:09,463
It's your new pet.

264
00:18:09,672 --> 00:18:11,591
Come on, Barney.
Be a good dog.

265
00:18:21,475 --> 00:18:23,269
You're kidding.

266
00:18:26,188 --> 00:18:28,065
Dad, it's really neat.

267
00:18:31,193 --> 00:18:32,278
Where'd you get this?

268
00:18:32,528 --> 00:18:34,989
Some little junk store in Chinatown.

269
00:18:35,197 --> 00:18:38,200
- Can I pick him up?
- Sure, go ahead. Just be careful.

270
00:18:38,451 --> 00:18:39,994
- You gotta be gentle.
- I will.

271
00:18:41,162 --> 00:18:42,872
I hope he's housebroken.

272
00:18:45,124 --> 00:18:46,709
Isn't he cute?

273
00:18:48,210 --> 00:18:49,295
Has it got a name?

274
00:18:49,503 --> 00:18:50,713
<i>Mogwai</i>.

275
00:18:51,005 --> 00:18:53,007
- What?
- <i>Mogwai</i>.

276
00:18:53,674 --> 00:18:56,218
Some Chinese word. I just call him...

277
00:18:56,427 --> 00:18:59,013
...Gizmo. He seems to like it.

278
00:19:03,559 --> 00:19:05,061
Look up here a minute.

279
00:19:06,187 --> 00:19:08,230
We're getting our picture taken.

280
00:19:08,439 --> 00:19:09,440
Smile.

281
00:19:09,690 --> 00:19:10,858
Ready?

282
00:19:11,067 --> 00:19:13,736
One, two, three...

283
00:19:15,071 --> 00:19:16,364
- No, no.
- Bright light!

284
00:19:16,572 --> 00:19:17,698
What happened?

285
00:19:17,907 --> 00:19:19,659
He hates bright lights.

286
00:19:20,451 --> 00:19:23,245
There's some important
things I forgot to tell you.

287
00:19:23,496 --> 00:19:28,584
Number one, he hates bright lights.
You gotta keep him out of the sunlight.

288
00:19:29,335 --> 00:19:30,920
Sunlight will kill him.

289
00:19:31,337 --> 00:19:33,756
Number two, keep him away from water.

290
00:19:34,048 --> 00:19:39,095
Don't give him any water to drink.
Whatever you do, don't give him a bath.

291
00:19:39,345 --> 00:19:41,597
And the most important thing...

292
00:19:41,847 --> 00:19:45,726
...don't ever feed him after midnight.

293
00:20:57,673 --> 00:20:58,674
Shh!

294
00:21:01,927 --> 00:21:03,345
Looks like you hurt yourself.

295
00:21:05,598 --> 00:21:07,475
Light bright! Light bright!

296
00:21:10,853 --> 00:21:14,982
Just sit down there
and don't fall off, okay?

297
00:21:15,191 --> 00:21:17,485
I'll get you fixed up in no time.

298
00:21:20,196 --> 00:21:21,864
All right.

299
00:21:22,865 --> 00:21:24,158
Hold still.

300
00:21:25,159 --> 00:21:27,495
Sorry. Sorry.

301
00:21:34,668 --> 00:21:37,087
Try not to move so much, okay?

302
00:21:55,105 --> 00:21:57,525
Good night, Giz.
I'll see you in the morning.

303
00:22:48,659 --> 00:22:50,286
Hello!

304
00:22:51,579 --> 00:22:52,913
Mrs. Peltzer?

305
00:22:55,958 --> 00:22:57,459
I got a tree!

306
00:22:58,460 --> 00:23:00,296
Oh, Christ!

307
00:23:01,964 --> 00:23:03,757
Billy!

308
00:23:08,721 --> 00:23:11,307
I just brought in your Christmas tree.

309
00:23:11,557 --> 00:23:13,100
What happened?

310
00:23:13,309 --> 00:23:16,395
Slight problem with the
Peltzer Peeler-Juicer.

311
00:23:16,604 --> 00:23:19,064
I thought your dad fixed it.

312
00:23:19,273 --> 00:23:20,941
I thought so too.

313
00:23:22,818 --> 00:23:26,572
You should just buy orange juice
in cartons. It's a lot easier.

314
00:23:27,781 --> 00:23:29,700
See, it works.

315
00:23:34,580 --> 00:23:37,082
<i>- I had to come.
- So I see.</i>

316
00:23:37,291 --> 00:23:39,251
<i>Now I can see. It takes...</i>

317
00:23:39,460 --> 00:23:41,003
<i>...a certain kind of guy.</i>

318
00:23:41,211 --> 00:23:44,089
<i>And that guy needs
a certain kind of dame.</i>

319
00:24:04,985 --> 00:24:07,154
It's no problem, Pete.
Leave it up here.

320
00:24:07,363 --> 00:24:08,530
What'll you tell him?

321
00:24:08,781 --> 00:24:12,743
I'll just tell him a bunch of bikers
stole it from me on my way home.

322
00:24:16,038 --> 00:24:18,874
Wow! <i>The Hooded Menace.</i>
Issue number one!

323
00:24:19,124 --> 00:24:20,376
Pretty neat, huh?

324
00:24:20,626 --> 00:24:22,044
Where'd you get it?

325
00:24:22,753 --> 00:24:24,755
Dr. Fantasy's, I think.

326
00:24:26,256 --> 00:24:28,884
- What's that?
- Come here. I'll show you.

327
00:24:29,510 --> 00:24:31,553
This is my new pet.
My dad gave him to me.

328
00:24:31,804 --> 00:24:33,055
Neat! What's his name?

329
00:24:33,305 --> 00:24:35,557
His name's Gizmo. Hi, Giz.

330
00:24:35,766 --> 00:24:37,476
He's a <i>mogwai</i>.

331
00:24:44,066 --> 00:24:45,401
Cute!

332
00:24:49,405 --> 00:24:51,031
Blink your eyes.

333
00:24:51,407 --> 00:24:54,576
Go like that.
Can you do that?

334
00:25:01,083 --> 00:25:02,710
Watch. Maybe he'll sing.

335
00:25:03,502 --> 00:25:07,339
Come on, Giz.
Let's go over to the table.

336
00:25:07,589 --> 00:25:08,924
I'll be careful.

337
00:25:10,426 --> 00:25:12,302
There we go.

338
00:25:15,055 --> 00:25:18,017
Gee, Billy, where can
I get one of those?

339
00:25:18,225 --> 00:25:21,061
I don't know.
This is the only one I've ever seen.

340
00:25:22,104 --> 00:25:23,105
Can I hold him?

341
00:25:23,355 --> 00:25:27,109
Sure. I don't see why not.
He seems to like you.

342
00:25:28,235 --> 00:25:30,446
Great! Thanks a lot.

343
00:25:30,696 --> 00:25:31,905
Sorry.

344
00:25:32,531 --> 00:25:33,949
What was in that jar?

345
00:25:34,199 --> 00:25:35,701
Nothing! Just water!

346
00:25:36,869 --> 00:25:38,287
Why is he making that noise?

347
00:25:46,086 --> 00:25:47,671
What is it?

348
00:25:47,838 --> 00:25:48,964
I don't know.

349
00:25:53,635 --> 00:25:55,471
Is it alive?

350
00:25:56,055 --> 00:25:57,473
I don't know.

351
00:26:57,491 --> 00:26:59,910
One, two, three, four, five new ones.

352
00:27:00,994 --> 00:27:02,663
Now can I have one?

353
00:27:02,913 --> 00:27:03,956
I don't know.

354
00:27:04,206 --> 00:27:06,708
Look, that one's got
a cute stripe on its head.

355
00:27:11,547 --> 00:27:13,048
Isn't that incredible, Pete?

356
00:27:13,340 --> 00:27:15,134
Yeah, great.

357
00:27:15,843 --> 00:27:18,554
Don't you think this...?
This is incredible!

358
00:27:19,555 --> 00:27:21,306
Oh, it is neat.

359
00:27:22,933 --> 00:27:24,726
I'm serious. It's neat.

360
00:27:28,730 --> 00:27:31,066
Gizmo, what's the matter?

361
00:27:45,539 --> 00:27:47,749
- No, no, no.
- Hey, Dad?

362
00:27:49,585 --> 00:27:52,087
- There's something I should tell you.
- Look.

363
00:27:52,254 --> 00:27:54,256
You're familiar with the Bathroom Buddy?

364
00:27:54,506 --> 00:27:56,884
I have made an improvement.

365
00:27:57,092 --> 00:27:58,093
Watch this.

366
00:27:58,385 --> 00:28:02,264
Now, let's say you're
late for the big meeting.

367
00:28:02,472 --> 00:28:03,849
It's really important.

368
00:28:04,099 --> 00:28:08,061
You're on your way. You reach up.
You forgot to shave.

369
00:28:08,353 --> 00:28:11,273
What're you gonna do?
Under normal circumstances...

370
00:28:11,523 --> 00:28:13,275
...you are in trouble.

371
00:28:13,483 --> 00:28:16,236
But not if you have the Bathroom Buddy.

372
00:28:16,945 --> 00:28:18,280
Watch this.

373
00:28:20,490 --> 00:28:21,867
What do you think?

374
00:28:22,576 --> 00:28:24,119
That's pretty neat.

375
00:28:25,787 --> 00:28:26,872
What's this button?

376
00:28:31,084 --> 00:28:32,628
- Sorry, Dad.
- It's okay.

377
00:28:32,794 --> 00:28:33,837
I'm sorry.

378
00:28:34,004 --> 00:28:37,549
It's not your fault. I'm working on that.
I haven't finished that.

379
00:28:37,758 --> 00:28:41,261
I came up here because there's
a problem with the <i>mogwai</i>.

380
00:28:41,470 --> 00:28:43,013
Yeah, what's that?

381
00:28:44,139 --> 00:28:46,308
It multiplies with water.

382
00:28:48,477 --> 00:28:49,561
What?

383
00:28:52,814 --> 00:28:54,399
Do you see what I mean?

384
00:28:55,150 --> 00:28:57,152
I don't believe that.

385
00:28:57,402 --> 00:28:59,279
All that from water?
They got wet?

386
00:28:59,488 --> 00:29:00,822
Plain water.

387
00:29:05,160 --> 00:29:07,329
It's funny.
The new ones aren't like Gizmo.

388
00:29:07,537 --> 00:29:09,665
The striped one seems to be the leader.

389
00:29:09,831 --> 00:29:10,916
You know what?

390
00:29:11,333 --> 00:29:14,419
I'll bet every kid in America
would like one of these.

391
00:29:14,920 --> 00:29:17,172
They might replace the dog
as the family pet.

392
00:29:28,976 --> 00:29:30,018
Think about it.

393
00:29:30,310 --> 00:29:32,145
The Peltzer Pet.

394
00:29:34,106 --> 00:29:37,567
This could really be the big one.

395
00:29:58,338 --> 00:29:59,381
Barn?

396
00:30:01,508 --> 00:30:02,884
Barney?

397
00:30:27,492 --> 00:30:28,577
Barney?

398
00:30:31,121 --> 00:30:33,248
Barney, who did this to you?

399
00:30:33,540 --> 00:30:35,208
Hold on, I'll get you down.

400
00:30:35,417 --> 00:30:36,752
Stay still.

401
00:30:38,086 --> 00:30:41,590
Poor dog. Another minute and
he would've been a dog-sicle.

402
00:30:43,258 --> 00:30:47,220
All I know is that I'm positive
that I closed and locked the door.

403
00:30:48,555 --> 00:30:50,349
How else did she get to him?

404
00:30:50,557 --> 00:30:54,728
We can't point any fingers,
not even at Mrs. Deagle.

405
00:30:55,604 --> 00:30:58,899
She's been threatening him.
She'd love to get her hands on him.

406
00:30:59,107 --> 00:31:04,237
We don't have proof. We can't even find
footprints leading up to the house.

407
00:31:05,739 --> 00:31:08,950
I'm gonna take Barney
to your grandmother's.

408
00:31:09,242 --> 00:31:12,746
Take him there on the way to the convention,
pick him up on the way home.

409
00:31:12,954 --> 00:31:16,625
He'll be here for Christmas.
It'll be all right.

410
00:31:22,297 --> 00:31:24,299
I don't think we can drink this.

411
00:31:29,096 --> 00:31:30,597
Why not?

412
00:31:31,056 --> 00:31:32,682
What's wrong with this?

413
00:31:40,982 --> 00:31:42,317
Hey, Billy.

414
00:31:42,484 --> 00:31:44,152
Is that a <i>mogwai</i>?

415
00:31:44,319 --> 00:31:47,322
Yeah, I'm gonna have
Mr. Hanson check it out.

416
00:31:47,489 --> 00:31:51,243
And all of a sudden, there were
five new ones like this one.

417
00:31:52,911 --> 00:31:54,579
Now watch this.

418
00:32:31,825 --> 00:32:35,287
Can I keep one of these here,
run some tests on him?

419
00:32:36,538 --> 00:32:38,457
I think I can spare one.

420
00:32:47,757 --> 00:32:50,552
This is some Christmas,
Katie, I'll tell you.

421
00:32:50,760 --> 00:32:55,807
First the old bat closes the factory,
and now it's my goddamn plow.

422
00:32:56,016 --> 00:32:59,060
Mr. Futterman, guess what?
It's time to go home now.

423
00:32:59,269 --> 00:33:01,521
- How about one more beer?
- No, it's late.

424
00:33:01,730 --> 00:33:03,648
One more beer, I'll help you clean up.

425
00:33:03,857 --> 00:33:06,568
No, thanks, though.
It'll be okay.

426
00:33:09,488 --> 00:33:12,032
- It'll be okay.
- It will not be okay.

427
00:33:12,240 --> 00:33:16,411
I brought my plow in for a tune-up
and found it loaded with foreign parts.

428
00:33:16,786 --> 00:33:19,915
I mean, everything.
Gaskets, pistons, spark plugs.

429
00:33:20,207 --> 00:33:22,000
All of it's foreign.

430
00:33:22,417 --> 00:33:24,252
- Billy!
- Hi.

431
00:33:26,379 --> 00:33:27,839
Going home?

432
00:33:28,215 --> 00:33:29,424
Oh, yeah.

433
00:33:33,553 --> 00:33:34,846
Gremlins!

434
00:33:36,181 --> 00:33:38,266
You gotta watch out for foreigners.

435
00:33:38,517 --> 00:33:40,810
They plant gremlins in their machinery.

436
00:33:41,019 --> 00:33:44,856
The same gremlins brought down
our planes in the big one.

437
00:33:45,607 --> 00:33:47,067
That's right.

438
00:33:47,317 --> 00:33:48,818
World War II.

439
00:33:49,027 --> 00:33:50,028
Good old...

440
00:33:50,237 --> 00:33:52,614
...W-W-I-I.

441
00:33:56,576 --> 00:33:59,120
They're still shipping them over here.

442
00:33:59,329 --> 00:34:01,206
They put them in the cars, the TV.

443
00:34:01,414 --> 00:34:04,125
They put them in the radios
you stick in your ears.

444
00:34:04,417 --> 00:34:07,254
They put them in the watches.
Little teeny gremlins.

445
00:34:07,462 --> 00:34:10,966
It's not a good idea that you drive.
Why don't you walk home?

446
00:34:11,591 --> 00:34:14,386
You know, Katie, I think
maybe I'll walk home.

447
00:34:14,636 --> 00:34:17,639
- Good.
- It's a nice night.

448
00:34:21,810 --> 00:34:23,311
- Good night, kids.
- Good night.

449
00:34:26,481 --> 00:34:28,108
Gremlins.

450
00:34:54,676 --> 00:34:58,179
That was really good, the way
you handled Mr. Futterman.

451
00:34:58,597 --> 00:35:00,181
I'm used to it.

452
00:35:00,682 --> 00:35:03,518
He's been like that ever
since he lost his job.

453
00:35:04,436 --> 00:35:08,940
He's like a lot of people around here.
He just wants somebody to listen.

454
00:35:09,149 --> 00:35:11,026
Especially around the holidays.

455
00:35:12,193 --> 00:35:13,653
Why is that?

456
00:35:13,862 --> 00:35:16,698
It's when a lot of people
get really depressed.

457
00:35:18,033 --> 00:35:22,704
I always thought everyone was happy
during the holidays, no matter what.

458
00:35:22,912 --> 00:35:25,540
Most people are, but some aren't.

459
00:35:25,707 --> 00:35:29,878
While everybody else opens up presents,
they're opening up their wrists.

460
00:35:31,171 --> 00:35:32,213
Cheery thought.

461
00:35:32,380 --> 00:35:36,051
It's true. The suicide rate's always
the highest around the holidays.

462
00:35:37,552 --> 00:35:39,429
Now I'm depressed.

463
00:35:39,721 --> 00:35:41,806
Do you ever get depressed on Christmas?

464
00:35:43,183 --> 00:35:45,060
I don't celebrate Christmas.

465
00:35:45,310 --> 00:35:46,686
Are you Hindu or something?

466
00:35:46,895 --> 00:35:48,813
No, I just don't like to.

467
00:35:50,065 --> 00:35:52,734
What's not to like?
I mean, it's a lot of fun.

468
00:35:53,026 --> 00:35:54,069
God!

469
00:35:54,319 --> 00:35:56,821
Say you hate Thanksgiving,
and nobody cares.

470
00:35:57,030 --> 00:36:01,534
But say you hate Christmas, everybody
makes you feel like you're a leper.

471
00:36:04,037 --> 00:36:05,997
- I'm sorry.
- It's okay.

472
00:36:06,206 --> 00:36:10,502
I'm sorry.
I'm just a little tired and cranky.

473
00:36:10,752 --> 00:36:12,045
Yeah.

474
00:36:15,757 --> 00:36:17,425
Thanks for walking me home.

475
00:36:17,676 --> 00:36:19,678
No problem.

476
00:36:20,387 --> 00:36:21,554
- Good night.
- Good night.

477
00:36:22,555 --> 00:36:23,765
Kate?

478
00:36:26,601 --> 00:36:30,563
I was just wondering, do you get
any free nights off from Dorry's?

479
00:36:31,731 --> 00:36:33,191
Thursdays.

480
00:36:33,775 --> 00:36:35,694
Thursdays, yeah.

481
00:36:35,902 --> 00:36:38,488
Because I was just wondering...

482
00:36:38,697 --> 00:36:43,201
...if you're free this Thursday night,
maybe you'd like to go out on a date...

483
00:36:44,285 --> 00:36:45,328
...with me?

484
00:36:45,495 --> 00:36:46,621
I'd love to.

485
00:36:48,540 --> 00:36:49,749
Oh, yeah?

486
00:36:49,999 --> 00:36:51,584
Well, that's great!

487
00:36:53,044 --> 00:36:57,382
We can talk about it
on the phone and kind of...

488
00:36:57,632 --> 00:36:59,592
...square everything away.

489
00:37:01,678 --> 00:37:03,138
Good night, Billy.

490
00:37:11,312 --> 00:37:12,647
'Night.

491
00:37:30,498 --> 00:37:31,875
Hey there.

492
00:37:34,878 --> 00:37:37,547
Give me your arm, boy.
Come here, come on.

493
00:37:37,839 --> 00:37:40,675
Give me your arm.
No, this is not gonna hurt.

494
00:37:41,551 --> 00:37:43,386
This isn't gonna hurt.

495
00:37:43,678 --> 00:37:47,140
Not a big guy like you. Come on.

496
00:37:47,390 --> 00:37:51,269
There you go.
See, that's not so bad. Come on.

497
00:37:51,561 --> 00:37:54,397
Good, good.
Oh, that's good.

498
00:37:55,190 --> 00:37:58,526
Just a little blood test, pal.
You'll never miss it.

499
00:38:02,655 --> 00:38:05,033
<i>They're like huge seedpods!</i>

500
00:38:11,790 --> 00:38:14,083
- Having fun?
- Fun!

501
00:38:14,292 --> 00:38:15,543
Pretty neat, huh?

502
00:38:15,752 --> 00:38:16,920
Neat!

503
00:38:18,755 --> 00:38:20,465
Yum, yum! Yum, yum!

504
00:38:24,719 --> 00:38:27,222
How about shutting up
for a change, okay?

505
00:38:27,430 --> 00:38:29,057
I already fed you.

506
00:38:35,772 --> 00:38:38,233
Well, it's not 12:00 yet.

507
00:38:38,900 --> 00:38:42,946
All right. Keep an eye on them, Giz.
I'll be back in a second.

508
00:39:04,133 --> 00:39:05,593
Here we go.

509
00:39:05,802 --> 00:39:08,763
Now maybe you guys will be quiet.

510
00:39:19,649 --> 00:39:21,276
You guys are really hungry.

511
00:39:24,279 --> 00:39:25,947
Giz, you want some?

512
00:39:29,951 --> 00:39:31,369
Do you want some chicken?

513
00:39:32,495 --> 00:39:34,122
No?

514
00:39:34,455 --> 00:39:35,665
All right.

515
00:39:42,797 --> 00:39:44,299
Yum, yum.

516
00:39:54,976 --> 00:39:57,645
That's it, good buddy.
